  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of people I know. Growing up in a working-class neighborhood in Rome, I never had the chance to explore advanced math or physics in school, but I always felt that my intelligence was being questioned by teachers who assumed I wasn't cut out for these subjects. That anxiety, that fear of confirming a stereotype about my abilities, is what stereotype threat really is. It's not just about being labeled 'less capable'—it's about the emotional toll it takes when you're constantly worried that your performance might reinforce negative beliefs about your group. For someone like me, who's never had a university education beyond a vocational diploma, this fear is especially real. Should we address it? Absolutely. But it's not about fixing people's minds—it's about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try. I volunteer at a community center in Rome where kids from disadvantaged backgrounds learn basic coding, and I've noticed that when we focus on their interests first—like how to build something useful with their hands—instead of pushing them to conform to traditional STEM expectations, they perform better. It's about listening, adapting, and making sure no one feels like they're failing because of who they are, not because of what they're trying to do.",
